Unsupervised Learning

Background

Unsupervised learning is a type of machine learning method which involves the process of learning patterns from the input data where the ground truth is either not known or not referred to.

The most common unsupervised learning method is the cluster analysis, which is used for exploratory data analysis to find grouping(s) or hidden patterns in data. This grouping is also called a partition in Computer Science. The clusters are identified using a measure of similarity which is defined upon metrics such as Euclidean or probabilistic distance. The cluster analysis groups the data that has not been labeled, not classified or not categorized. Instead of responding to feedback (target/dependent variable), cluster analysis identifies commonalities in the data and reacts based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.

The simplest form of clustering can be considered as the binning process as in data preprocessing, where the input numerical values are grouped according to the ranges of the bins.

  • Supervised learning intends to infer a conditional probability distribution PX(x|y)PX(x|y) conditioned on the labels yy of input data
  • Unsupervised learning intends to infer an a priori probability distribution PX(x)PX(x)

Unsupervised learning is the first form of learning which is much more common in the brain.

Clustering is the main method of unsupervised learning which can answer questions like,

  • What is the "normal" in the dataset? What is the baseline?
  • Which data points are abnormal, anomalous in the dataset, if there are any?
  • Is there a probability distribution that can model the input dataset?
  • How many clusters are there in the dataset naturally?
  • Anomaly detection

Types of clustering:

Hard clustering: Each data point can be assigned to one cluster only
Soft clustering: Also known as fuzzy clustering, where each data point can have a membership value to any cluster.

Major Clustering Algorithms

Distance/Similarity Measures

All clustering algorithms employ some form of similarity or a distance measure.

A distance metric, d:XX[0,)d:XX[0,), satisfies the following:

  • d(x,y)0d(x,y)0 non-negative
  • d(x,y)=0x=yd(x,y)=0x=y identity
  • d(x,y)=d(y,x)d(x,y)=d(y,x) symmetry
  • d(x,y)d(x,z)+d(z,y)d(x,y)d(x,z)+d(z,y) triangle inequality

Define dikdik = the distance between xixi and the cluster center ckck where k=1,,Kk=1,,K, and xRNxMxRNxM and ckRMckRM

  • Euclidean distance dik=Mj=0(xijckj)2dik=j=0M(xijckj)2
  • Manhattan distance dik=Mj=0|xijckj|dik=j=0M|xijckj|
  • Chebyshev distance dik=maxj|xijckj|dik=maxj|xijckj|
  • Cosine similarity dik=cos()=xickxickdik=cos()=xickxick
  • Jaccard index dik=xickxickdik=xickxick

K-means Clustering Algorithm

K-means clustering aims to partition NN data points into KK number of clusters in which each observation belongs to the cluster with the nearest mean (i.e. cluster centroid).

  1. Randomly pick KK data points from the input data set as initial cluster centers, call kk where k=1,,Kk=1,,K.
  2. Assign each data point xixi to the cluster via the nearest centroid kk where k=1,,Kk=1,,K.
  3. Recompute (move) the centroids to the center of the data points of respective clusters.
  4. Repeat steps 2 and 3 until the cluster assignments do not change or a user-defined tolerance or a pre-defined maximum number of iterations is reached.

Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise (DBSCAN)

DBSCAN is a density-based clustering algorithm that groups points when they are closely packed together (points with many nearby neighbors). Algorithm marks the data points as outliers when they lie alone in low-density regions (whose nearest neighbors are too far away).

  1. Find the points in the EE-neighborhood of every point, and identify the core points with more than minimum Data Points neighbors.
  2. Find the connected components of core points on the neighbor graph, ignoring all non-core points.
  3. Assign each non-core point to a nearby cluster if the cluster is an EE-neighbor, otherwise assign it to noise.

Hierarchical Clustering

Hierarchical clustering seeks to build a hierarchy of clusters.

Agglomerative, bottom-up approach where each observation starts in its own cluster, and pairs of clusters are merged as one moves up the hierarchy. Example draft algorithm:

  1. Compute the distance matrix DD of all data points, i.e. NxNNxN size.
  2. Represent each data point as a singleton cluster.
  3. Merge the two closest clusters based on the distance between the most dissimilar (distant) members of those two clusters.
  4. Update the similarity matrix.
  5. Repeat steps 2-4 until one single cluster remains

Divisive, top-down approach where all observations start in one cluster, and splits are performed recursively as one moves down the hierarchy. Example draft algorithm:

  1. Assign all data points to one cluster.
  2. For each cluster kk where k=1,,Kk=1,,K, find the most dissimilar (distant) member xk1xk1 to its centroid kk and find the most dissimilar member xk2xk2 to xk1xk1
  3. Identify the kk with the highest dissimilarity between xk1xk1 and xk2xk2 where k=1,,Kk=1,,K
  4. Make xk1xk1 and xk2xk2 new cluster centers, remove the original cluster center kk and re-assign all data points to the closest cluster centers.
  5. Repeat steps 2-4 until each data point is a singleton.

Hierarchical methods cluster everything (either agglomerative or divisive) and let the user deciding about the number of clusters desired, since every possible number of clusters is already computed.

Expectation Maximization

Expectation maximization algorithm is an iterative method to find maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimates of parameters (such as mean and standard deviation) in statistical models. Example draft algorithm:

  1. Start with an initial estimate of what each parameter might be.
  2. Compute the likelihood that each parameter produces the data point, i.e. compute the probability of each data point belonging to a particular cluster, which is a Gaussian distribution.
  3. Calculate weights for each data point indicating whether it is more red or more blue based on the likelihood of it being produced by a parameter. Combine the weights with the data (expectation).
  4. Compute a better estimate for the parameters using the weight-adjusted data (maximization).
  5. Repeat steps 2-4 until the parameter estimate converges (the process stops producing a different estimate).

where dkldkl is the distance between cluster kk centroid and cluster ll centroid. Note that dkkdkk is zero. A good clustering algorithm maximizes this metric.

EkEk is the average distance between the cluster centroid and the data points of that cluster kk. A good clustering algorithm minimizes this metric.

Scoring Clustering

Regular accuracy, i.e. Accuracy=#correct#totalAccuracy=#correct#total

Rand Index

After a clustering the cluster indexes may not match the original cluster indexes literally. The contingency_matrix function from the library sklearn.metrics.cluster can be used to map the resulting clusters to the original clusters (i.e. ground truth).

Given a set of nn elements S={o1,,on}S={o1,,on} and two partitions of SS to compare, X={X1,,Xr}X={X1,,Xr}, a partition of SS into rr subsets, and Y={Y1,,Ys}Y={Y1,,Ys}, a partition of SS into ss subsets, define the following:

  • aa, the number of pairs of elements in SS that are in the same subset in XX and in the same subset in YY
  • bb, the number of pairs of elements in SS that are in different subsets in XX and in different subsets in YY
  • cc, the number of pairs of elements in SS that are in the same subset in XX and in different subsets in YY
  • dd, the number of pairs of elements in SS that are in different subsets in XX and in the same subset in YY

The Rand index, R=a+ba+b+c+d=a+b(n2)R=a+ba+b+c+d=a+b(n2)

Intuitively, a+ba+b can be considered as the number of agreements between XX and YY and c+dc+d as the number of disagreements between XX and YY.

Since the denominator is the total number of pairs, the Rand index represents the frequency of occurrence of agreements over the total pairs, or the probability that XX and YY will agree on a randomly chosen pair.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs

def get_minmax(_X, _m):  # _m = margin for visuals
    return _X[:,0].min()-_m, _X[:,0].max()+_m, _X[:,1].min()-_m, _X[:,1].max()+_m

def plotX(_X, _y, ax=None):  # Max 5 clusters/classes
    Colors = ['darkorchid', 'darkgreen', 'darkgrey', 'darksalmon', 'darkseagreen']
    Markers = ['o', '+', 'x', '1', '.']
    for c in range(max(_y)+1):
        plt.scatter(_X[_y==c,0], _X[_y==c,1], marker=Markers[c], color=Colors[c])
    #
    if ax is not None:
        ax.get_xaxis().set_ticks([])
        ax.get_yaxis().set_ticks([])
    #
    x1_min, x1_max, x2_min, x2_max = get_minmax(_X, 1)
    plt.xlim(x1_min, x1_max)
    plt.ylim(x2_min, x2_max)
    plt.xlabel(r'$x_1$', horizontalalignment='right', x=1.0)
    plt.ylabel(r'$x_2$', horizontalalignment='right', y=1.0)

# 5 classes with 2 features
X, y = make_blobs(n_samples=(100, 500, 500, 500, 1000), n_features=2, random_state=1,
                  cluster_std=[2, .5, .5, .5, 5],
                  centers=[(-3, -3), (-3, 3), (3, -3), (3, 3), (6, 6)])

plotX(X, y)

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics.cluster import contingency_matrix
from sklearn.metrics import adjusted_rand_score

def kmeans_k(_n_clusters, _X, _y):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=_n_clusters, init='random',
                n_init=10, max_iter=300, random_state=42)
    return km.fit_predict(_X), km.inertia_

def get_matchratio(_y, _y_km):
    # Compute contingency matrix
    cm = np.argmax(contingency_matrix(_y_km, _y), axis=1)
    # Map the clusters to the original using contingency above
    predicted = np.array([cm[c] for c in _y_km])
    # Compute match ratio, or accuracy
    match = sum([1 for y1, y2 in zip(_y, predicted) if y1 == y2])
    # Return the accuracy and mapped predictions
    return match/len(_y), predicted

EXPERIMENTS_K = (2,3,4,5,6,8,10)

for k in EXPERIMENTS_K:
    y_pred, inertia = kmeans_k(k, X, y)
    print(f'K-means with k={k:02d} performance, match rate={get_matchratio(y, y_pred)[0]:.3f}, '+
          f'Adjusted Rand index={adjusted_rand_score(y, y_pred):.3f}')

acc, inertia = [], []

    y_pred, iner = kmeans_k(k, X, y)
    ac, pred = get_matchratio(y, y_pred)
    acc += [ac]
    inertia += [iner]

Important: Notice that by using contingency mapping we are not reporting the true clustering error when we assign different cluster IDs to different parts of the same cluster. Thus, the following modification to the accuracy computation is realized, albeit probably penalizing the additional clusterings harshly.

Once a kmeans cluster is assigned to a particular original cluster, that original cluster ID is not used anymore. All remaining unassigned clusters are assigned to new cluster IDs, so that error will accumulate.

In [6]:
def get_matchratio2(_y, _y_km):
    # Compute contingency matrix
    cm = np.argmax(contingency_matrix(_y_km, _y), axis=1)
    # Modification to contingency cluster mapping
    k_new = len(np.unique(_y))  # assumes y has consequent labels of 0, 1, 2, ..
    gt_dict = {k:0 for k in range(k_new)}
    for i, c in enumerate(cm):
        if gt_dict[c] == 0:
            gt_dict[c] = 1
        else:
            cm[i] = k_new
            k_new += 1
    # Map the clusters to the original using contingency above
    predicted2 = np.array([cm[c] for c in _y_km])
    # Compute match ratio, or accuracy
    match = sum([1 for y1, y2 in zip(_y, predicted2) if y1 == y2])
    # Return the accuracy and mapped predictions
    return match/len(_y), predicted2

def draw3d(df_ser1, df_ser2, df_ser3, df_ser_c):
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
    ax.set_xlim3d(df_ser1.min()-0.1, df_ser1.max()+0.1)
    ax.set_ylim3d(df_ser2.min()-0.1, df_ser2.max()+0.1)
    ax.set_zlim3d(df_ser3.min()-0.1, df_ser3.max()+0.1)
    ax.set_ylim(ax.get_ylim()[::-1])
    ax.scatter(df_ser1, df_ser2, df_ser3, c=df_ser_c, s=30)

In [18]:
from collections import defaultdict
from functools import partial

def get_centroids(_X, _y):
    U = defaultdict(partial(np.ndarray, 0))
    Cn = defaultdict(int)
    for x, c in zip(_X, _y):
        U[c] = x if Cn[c] == 0 else U[c] + x
        Cn[c] += 1
    for c in U.keys():
        U[c] /= Cn[c]
    return U

def distance_inter_cluster(_U, _dist):
    # Compute inter-cluster errors
    K = np.max([int(c) for c in _U.keys()]) + 1
    if K < 2:
        return 0
    err, n = 0, 0
    for i in range(K):
        for j in range(i+1,K):
            err += _dist(_U[i], _U[j])
            n += 1
    return err / n

def distance_intra_cluster(_X, _y_km, _dist):
    # Compute intra-cluster errors
    U = get_centroids(_X, _y_km)
    En = defaultdict(partial(np.ndarray, 0))
    Cn = defaultdict(int)
    for x, c in zip(_X, _y_km):
        En[c] = _dist(x, U[c]) if Cn[c] == 0 else En[c] + _dist(x, U[c])
        Cn[c] += 1
    for c in U.keys():
        En[c] /= Cn[c]
    return En

    y_km, intertia = kmeans_k(k, X, y)
    U = get_centroids(X, y_km)
    for c in sorted(U.keys()):
        print(f"{k}-means centroid {c}  [{' '.join([f'{x_:.2f}' for x_ in U[c]]):s}]")

    intercluster_vector = distance_inter_cluster(U, dist)
    intercluster_magnitude = np.linalg.norm(intercluster_vector)
    print(f'average inter-cluster distance= {intercluster_magnitude:.3f}')
    intracluster_vector = distance_intra_cluster(X, y_km, dist)
    for c in sorted(intracluster_vector.keys()):
        intracluster_magnitude = np.linalg.norm(intracluster_vector[c])
        print(f'cluster {c} intra-distance= {intracluster_magnitude:.3f}')

    print('-------------------------------------------------------------')

Dendrograms for Hierarchical Clustering

The following cell demonstrates a simple dendrogram for uniform distances for three linkages types: {ward, complete, and single}. Full set of distances could be computed by the clustering program when clusters are joined, i.e. the distances between cluster centroids.

The x-axis is the individual data points, i.e. elements to be clustered. The y-axis levels are the clustering levels which is determined by the number of data points NN.

In [23]:
from scipy.cluster.hierarchy import linkage, dendrogram

def plot_dendrogram_iris(_model, titletext='', **kwargs):
    # uniform distances
    distances = np.arange(_model.children_.shape[0])
    
    # number of observations contained in each clustering level
    no_of_observations = np.arange(2, _model.children_.shape[0]+2)
    
    # linkage matrix
    linkage_matrix = np.column_stack([_model.children_, distances, no_of_observations]).astype(float)
    
    # dendrogram plotting
    dendrogram(linkage_matrix, **kwargs)
    plt.title(f'Iris dataset Dendrogram ({titletext})')
    plt.xlabel('sample index')
    
# Plot
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 6), dpi=72)

plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
model = AgglomerativeClustering(linkage='ward')
model.fit_predict(X)
plot_dendrogram_iris(model, titletext='ward')
plt.ylabel('Distance')
    
plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
model = AgglomerativeClustering(linkage='complete')
model.fit_predict(X)
plot_dendrogram_iris(model, titletext='complete')

plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
model = AgglomerativeClustering(linkage='single')
model.fit_predict(X)
plot_dendrogram_iris(model, titletext='single')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
